\description{
These functions are assertion factories: they produce assertions that take an
object, check conditions, and return the input, usually unmodified. The
assertion factories documented here never modify their inputs.

The factory names and the general assertion-factory pattern follow the original
\href{https://github.com/moodymudskipper/typed}{typed} package. typedr keeps
that interface and modernizes the implementation with rlang predicates, cli
errors, and typed condition classes.

Additional conditions can be provided through \code{...}:
\itemize{
\item Named arguments should name a predicate or accessor to call on the checked
object, with the argument value giving the expected result.
\item Unnamed arguments should be formulas. The right-hand side is a condition
that can use \code{value} or \code{.} as a placeholder for the checked object. In
two-sided formulas, the left-hand side is used as the error message.
}

\code{Any()} is the most general assertion factory: it doesn't check anything
unless additional conditions are provided through \code{...}. Other assertion
factories use the relevant base \verb{is.<type>} function when available, check
\code{typeof()} for atomic types, or check that the class of the checked value
contains the relevant class.

See advanced examples at the bottom, including uses of \code{Symbol()} and \code{Dots()}.
}
